03758nam a22006375i 9780814738504DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19981998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147385047 a10.18574/97808147385042doi  a(DE-B1597)547954  a(OCoLC)782877950  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF8725b.G65 1998 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a347.73/52211 aGoldfarb, Ronald L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTV or Not TV :bTelevision, Justice, and the Courts /cRonald L. Goldfarb. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter 1. The Trial of the Century -- tChapter 2. The Free Press, the Fair and Public Trial: -- tChapter 3. Cameras in the Courts: -- tChapter 4. A Thing Observed, a Thing Changed: -- tChapter 5. The Crucible: Court TV -- tChapter 6. TV or Not TV -- tAppendix A: Camera Coverage in the States -- tAppendix B: Summary of State Camera Coverage Rules by the Radio-Television News Directors Association -- tNOTES -- tINDEX -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last quarter century, televised court proceedings have gone from an outlandish idea to a seemingly inevitable reality. Yet,debate continues to rage over the dangers and benefits to the justice system of cameras in the courtroom. Critics contend television transforms the temple of justice into crass theatre. Supporters maintain that silent cameras portray "the real thing," that without them judicial reality is inevitably filtered through the mind and pens of a finite pool of reporters. Television in a courtroom is clearly a two-edged sword, both invasive and informative. Bringing a trial to the widest possible audience creates pressures and temptations for all participants. While it reduces speculations and fears about what transpired, television sometimes forces the general public, which possesses information the jury may not have, into a conflicting assessment of specific cases and the justice system in general. TV or Not TV argues convincingly that society gains much more than it loses when trials are open to public scrutiny and discussion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aConduct of court proceedingszUnited States. 0aFree press and fair trialzUnited States. 0aTelevision broadcasting of court proceedingszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814738504423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814738504.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK